Product Quality Based on Green and Dry Boards

JH

7/24/2015

  • 1 Background
  • 2 Hyne Dataset
  • 3 Board Level Comparisons
  • 4 Log Level Comparisons
  • 5 Site Level Comparisons
  • 6 Predicting Log Average Board Stiffness
  • 7 Conclusions and Recommendations

1 Background

The eCambium trial to be run later in 2015 hopes to use green board density and stress wave velocity (SWV) to estimate product quality at individual log and site levels.

In the eCambium context, product quality equates to stiffness. In the grain direction wood is typically only 10% stiffer when dry compared to green.

Green board properties are to be measured using a Calibre Ecoustic device installed in Hynes Tumbarumba green mill. This device uses load cells to measure board weight and a hammer/microphone to measure stress wave velocity. These measures are combined with a dimensions from the USNR trimmer scanner to yield board green density which in turn is combined with SWV to yield an estimate of board MOE (currently \(E = \rho v^2\)). In situations where measurement quality is poor, a default MOE of 6.50 GPa is assigned. Currently, only weight, density and predicted MOE are written to the Ecoustic results file.

2 Hyne Dataset

SWI collected put 123 logs through Hynes Tumbarumba mill in 2014/15. The resulting dataset include green as well as dry board measures.

Associating boards with logs in the Hyne green mill makes use of:

  • Calibre Ecoustic csv results file (collected after trimsaw)
  • board LE imagery (collected before trimsaw)
  • USNR database information (e.g.TRIMMER2.FlitchDetail)
library(lattice)
library(gridExtra)
## Loading required package: grid
library(RODBC)
ch = odbcConnect('Hyne',uid='sa',pwd="password12")
#
# BOARDS
# 
B = sqlQuery(ch, "
            select
              m.flitchId, SWILogNumber,
               g.MOE [E.g], 
               g.Density [den.g], 
               m.swv [v.d], 
               h.[Density_kg/m3] [den.d], 
               h.[MOE.cltraw] [E.d], 
               m.pith, 
               m.wane, 
               X_MOE/1000. [E.d.chh],
               X_Dens [den.d.chh]
            from 
               (select flitchId, max(pith) pith, max(wane) wane, avg(swv) swv 
                from manualMeas 
                group by flitchId) m 
             left join HyneDryBoards h on h.flitchId=m.flitchId
             left join ecoustic g on m.flitchId=g.flitchId
             left join CHHBoards c on m.flitchId=c.flitchId
             left join (
                select flitchId, max(SWILogNumber) SWILogNumber 
                from boardEndImages i, barcode_image bi, boardEndBarcodes b 
                where flitchId is not null and i.id=bi.imageId and bi.barcodeId=b.id group by flitchId
             ) f on f.flitchId=m.flitchId
             where g.MOE>0 and g.MOE<>6.5 
             ")
B$pith_wane = paste("pith =",B$pith,"; wane =",B$wane)
B$E.d.hitman = B$v.d^2*B$den.d.chh/1e9
B$v.g = sqrt(B$E.g*1e9/B$den.g)
B$E.g.corrected = B$E.g
B$E.g.corrected[B$v.g>4000] = (B$v.g[B$v.g>4000]/2)^2*B$den.g[B$v.g>4000]/1e9
#
# LOGS
#
L = sqlQuery(ch, "
             select 
               p.*,
               t.SWV [SWV],
               t.weight,
               3.141592654*4.9/3*(rL*rL+rS*rL+rS*rS) [volume.heart]
             from 
               (select * 
                from logs 
                where SWILogNumber is not null 
                and DateAndTime>'2014-08-31 00:00:00') p
               left join (select * 
                          from logs 
                          where SWILogNumber is not null 
                          and DateAndTime<'2014-08-31 00:00:00') s 
                 on s.SWILogNumber=p.SWILogNumber
               left join yardTrimmed t 
                 on p.SWILogNumber=t.SWILogNumber 
               left join yardUntrimmed u 
                 on p.SWILogNumber=u.SWILogNumber 
               left join (select 
                            l.SWILogNumber, 
                            l.heartwoodDiameter_mm/2000 rL, 
                            s.heartwoodDiameter_mm/2000 rS 
                          from 
                            logends l, 
                            logends s 
                          where 
                            s.SWILogNumber=l.SWILogNumber 
                            and s.logEnd='S' 
                            and l.logEnd='L') h 
                 on h.SWILogNumber=p.SWILogNumber
             order by p.SWILogNumber")
for (i in 1:nrow(L)) {
  ii = !is.na(B$SWILogNumber) & B$SWILogNumber==L[i,"SWILogNumber"] 
  ii = ii & is.finite(B$E.g.corrected) & is.finite(B$E.d)
  L[i,"nboards"]=sum(ii)
  L[i,"avgBoardMOE.g"]=mean(B$E.g.corrected[ii],na.rm=TRUE)
  L[i,"avgBoardMOE.d"]=mean(B$E.d[ii],na.rm=TRUE)
}

3 Board Level Comparisons

xyplot(E.d ~ E.g, B, 
       group=pith_wane, 
       auto.key=TRUE, 
       panel=function(x,y,...) {
          panel.abline(c(0,1), col='grey70', lty=2)
          panel.xyplot(x,y,...)
       }, 
       xlab="Green MOE (ecoustic) / [GPa]", 
       ylab="Dry MOE (Metriguard CLT) / [GPa]",
       aspect='iso')

Around 5% have a green MOE twice what would be expected given the dry MOE. Most of these outliers are pith boards. Almost certainly they have an SWV that is twice what it should be (due to picking the 2nd harmonic instead of the fundamental). Fortunately these points all have incredible SWVs (>4 km/s) and so are easily detected and can be corrected.

After correction:

summary(m.board <- lm(E.d ~ E.g.corrected, B))
##

## (Intercept)    3.41549    0.11148   30.64   <2e-16 ***
## E.g.corrected  1.02381    0.01724   59.38   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.9826 on 666 degrees of freedom
##   (227 observations deleted due to missingness)
## Multiple R-squared:  0.8411, Adjusted R-squared:  0.8409 
## F-statistic:  3525 on 1 and 666 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
xyplot(E.d ~ E.g.corrected, B, 
       panel=function(x,y,...) {
          panel.abline(c(0,1), col='grey70', lty=2)
          panel.xyplot(x,y,...)
          panel.abline(coef(m.board), col='red')
       }, 
       xlab="Green MOE (ecoustic) / [GPa]", 
       ylab="Dry MOE (Metriguard CLT) / [GPa]",
       aspect='iso')

The fitted model suggests there is an offset between green and dry MOE but little in the way of a proportional increase (perhaps the increase in stiffness due to drying is offset by the decrease associated with static rather than dynamic measurement method). The offset is likely due to weights being systematically high (perhaps incorrectly calibrated load cells), an idea supported by a number of boards having green densities greater than 1200 kg/m^3.

Clearly, if the eCambium trial needs to convert green Ecoustic measurements to absolute dry MOE some sort of calibration dataset will be required, but in all likelihood, green MOE can be used as a relative measure directly, with an RMSE of around 1 GPa.

5 Site Level Comparisons

Site information is not directly available in the Hyne dataset. Instead lets look at results averaged over sets of 30 logs.

S = data.frame()
for (site in 1:100) {
  ii = B$SWILogNumber%in%sample(100:223, 30)
  S=rbind(S,data.frame(SWILogNumber=site,
                       avgBoardMOE.g=mean(B$E.g.corrected[ii], na.rm=TRUE),
                       avgBoardMOE.d=mean(B$E.d[ii], na.rm=TRUE)
                       ))
}
summary(m.site <- lm(avgBoardMOE.d ~ avgBoardMOE.g, S))

6 Predicting Log Average Board Stiffness

Slightly off-topic, but useful in case of dire failures in-mill

In cases where log average board stiffness is a sufficient measure of product quality (i.e.when less interested in relative distribution of board stiffnesses and more interested in the average value) then log level measures can be used instead of using green board MOE to predict dry board MOE. How well can log average board MOE be predicted from log level measurements?

myplot=function (m, lbl) {
  print(s<-summary(m))
  xyplot(m$model$avgBoardMOE.d ~ predict(m), 
         panel=function(x,y,...) {
           panel.abline(c(0,1), col='grey70', lty=2)
           panel.xyplot(x,y,...)}, 
          aspect='iso',
         xlab='Predicted', ylab='Actual',
         main=sprintf('%s\nr^2=%0.2f',lbl,s$r.squared))
         #main=lbl, sub=expression(r^2==s$r.squared))
}
grid.arrange(myplot(m.best.current, lbl="Current (SWV + volume)"), 
             myplot(m.best.withWeight, lbl="With Log Weight"), 
             myplot(m.best.withHW, lbl="With Log end HW"), 
             myplot(m.best.withWeightHW, lbl="With Log Weight and HW"), 
             myplot(m.best, lbl="Everything"),
             nrow=1, 
             as.table=TRUE)

With log weight and heartwood, \(r^2 = 0.7\), RMSE=0.9 GPa. Prediction quality similar to using green board MOE!

7 Conclusions and Recommendations

Ecoustic green MOE should do the job, particularly post-correction.

Previously collected green and dry MOE data should be helpful when testing for significant differences between log and sites.

Predicting log average board MOE from log measures alone is a credible alternative, particularly if log weight is known.

Some recommendations:

  1. The calibre output file be amended to include as-measured SWV (even if silly) as well as predicted MOE (retaining 6.5 GPa default). Ideally, some measure of confidence in the SWV should also be included.
  2. The ecoustic load cell calibrations be checked immediately before (and again after?) the trial is run
  3. Trim logs to random (but known) lengths (5 cm) to assist assigning boards to logs based on trimmer scanner data. Easiest if done within site batches.
  4. Put some effort into devising a quickneasy method of determining log weight.
  5. Ensure log volume and shape data collected.

If we really believed in prediction from log measures, could the trial be expanded without significantly increasing cost to include more logs, but processing only a subset?
